This project is a CMake project.

# launch ccmake to find appropriate package locations
ccmake .

# cmake to make Makefile, and make it
cmake .
make

# (if you are a kdevelop user)
cmake . -G KDevelop3
# then open the generated project file in kdevelop

If you are using KDevelop4, simply open the cmake files.


-- if you don't have log4cxx installed and you don't have permission
to install them in /usr or /usr/local (like Brown CS machines), 
download APR/APR-util/log4cxx and install them in your home directory.
For example:

mkdir /home/hkimura/modules
cd /home/hkimura/modules

# download and extract files here

cd apr-1.4.2/
./configure --prefix=/home/hkimura/modules
make
make install
cd ..

cd apr-util-1.3.9/
./configure --prefix=/home/hkimura/modules --with-apr=/home/hkimura/modules/apr-1.4.2
make
make install
cd ..

cd apache-log4cxx-0.10.0
./configure --prefix=/home/hkimura/modules --with-apr=/home/hkimura/modules/apr-1.4.2  --with-apr-util=/home/hkimura/modules/apr-util-1.3.9
make
make install

And then, specify the log4cxx folder in ccmake. for example:
 LOG4CXX_INCLUDE_DIRS            */home/hkimura/modules/include                
 LOG4CXX_LIBRARIES               */home/hkimura/modules/lib                    
 Log4cxx_FOUND                   *ON    

- one trouble in debian. I encountered a compilation error:
"inputstreamreader.cpp:66: error: 'memmove' was not declared in this scope"
I avoided this error by adding "#include <string.h>" in
src/main/cpp/inputstreamreader.cpp and src/main/cpp/socketoutputstream.cpp
and src/example/cpp/console.cpp


-- same thing to libdb/libdb_cxx and boost
